# 1. Develop a web page with non-semantic elements <div> and <span>
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Non-Semantic Elements Example</title>
    <style>
        /* General styling */
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f8f8f8;
            text-align: center;
            padding: 20px;
        }

        /* Styling for div container */
        .container {
            width: 50%;
            margin: auto;
            background-color: white;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 10px;
            box-shadow: 0px 4px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
        }

        /* Header inside div */
        .header {
            background-color: #3498db;
            color: white;
            padding: 15px;
            font-size: 24px;
            font-weight: bold;
            border-radius: 10px 10px 0 0;
        }

        /* Content section */
        .content {
            padding: 20px;
            text-align: left;
            font-size: 18px;
        }

        /* Styling for span */
        .highlight {
            color: red;
            font-weight: bold;
        }

        /* Footer inside div */
        .footer {
            background-color: #2c3e50;
            color: white;
            padding: 10px;
            font-size: 16px;
            border-radius: 0 0 10px 10px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <!-- Non-Semantic div used as a container -->
    <div class="container">
        
        <!-- Header section inside div -->
        <div class="header">Welcome to My Web Page</div>
        
        <!-- Content section inside div -->
        <div class="content">
            <p>This webpage is designed using <span class="highlight">non-semantic elements</span> like div and span.</p>
            <p>The <span class="highlight">div</span> tag is used to group content, and the <span class="highlight">span</span> tag is used to style inline elements.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Footer section inside div -->
        <div class="footer">&copy; 2025 MyWebsite. All Rights Reserved.</div>
    </div>

</body>
</html>

# 2. Develop a web page with the semantic elements <form>, <table> and <article>
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Semantic Elements Example</title>
    <style>
        /* General styling */
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            text-align: center;
            padding: 20px;
        }

        /* Container */
        .container {
            width: 60%;
            margin: auto;
            background-color: white;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 10px;
            box-shadow: 0px 4px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
        }

        /* Styling for Article */
        article {
            text-align: left;
            padding: 20px;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
            background-color: #f9f9f9;
            border-left: 5px solid #3498db;
        }

        article h2 {
            color: #3498db;
        }

        /* Styling for Form */
        form {
            text-align: left;
            padding: 20px;
            background-color: #ecf0f1;
            border-radius: 10px;
        }

        form label {
            font-weight: bold;
        }

        form input, form button {
            width: 100%;
            padding: 10px;
            margin: 5px 0;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }

        form button {
            background-color: #2c3e50;
            color: white;
            font-size: 16px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }

        form button:hover {
            background-color: #3498db;
        }

        /* Styling for Table */
        table {
            width: 100%;
            border-collapse: collapse;
            margin-top: 20px;
        }

        table, th, td {
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
        }

        th, td {
            padding: 10px;
            text-align: center;
        }

        th {
            background-color: #3498db;
            color: white;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <div class="container">

        <!-- Article Section -->
        <article>
            <h2>Understanding Semantic Elements</h2>
            <p>Semantic elements clearly define the purpose of the content. The `<article>` tag represents independent content, `<form>` is used for user input, and `<table>` is used to present data.</p>
        </article>

        <!-- Form Section -->
        <form>
            <h2>Contact Form</h2>
            <label for="name">Name:</label>
            <input type="text" id="name" name="name" placeholder="Enter your name" required>

            <label for="email">Email:</label>
            <input type="email" id="email" name="email" placeholder="Enter your email" required>

            <label for="message">Message:</label>
            <input type="text" id="message" name="message" placeholder="Your message" required>

            <button type="submit">Submit</button>
        </form>

        <!-- Table Section -->
        <table>
            <caption><strong>Student Grades</strong></caption>
            <tr>
                <th>Name</th>
                <th>Subject</th>
                <th>Grade</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Priya</td>
                <td>Math</td>
                <td>A</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Rahul</td>
                <td>Science</td>
                <td>B+</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Sneha</td>
                <td>English</td>
                <td>A-</td>
            </tr>
        </table>

    </div>

</body>
</html>

# 3. Use all the HTML5 tags and develop a web page article, aside, figcaption, figure,footer,header, hgroup,mark,nav, section,time
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>HTML5 Web Page Example</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
        }
        header {
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            color: white;
            padding: 20px;
            text-align: center;
        }
        nav {
            background-color: #333;
            overflow: hidden;
        }
        nav a {
            color: white;
            padding: 14px 20px;
            text-decoration: none;
            display: inline-block;
        }
        nav a:hover {
            background-color: #ddd;
            color: black;
        }
        section {
            padding: 20px;
        }
        footer {
            background-color: #333;
            color: white;
            text-align: center;
            padding: 10px;
            position: fixed;
            bottom: 0;
            width: 100%;
        }
        figure {
            text-align: center;
            margin: 0;
        }
        mark {
            background-color: yellow;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<header>
    <h1>Welcome to My HTML5 Web Page</h1>
    <hgroup>
        <h2>Your Source for Web Development</h2>
        <h3>Learning HTML5 Tags</h3>
    </hgroup>
</header>

<nav>
    <a href="#home">Home</a>
    <a href="#about">About</a>
    <a href="#contact">Contact</a>
</nav>

<section>
    <article>
        <h2>Understanding HTML5 Tags</h2>
        <p>HTML5 introduces several new tags that help organize content semantically and improve accessibility. <mark>Semantic HTML</mark> improves search engine optimization (SEO) and ensures that content is properly structured.</p>
        <time datetime="2025-03-08">March 8, 2025</time>
    </article>
    
    <article>
        <h2>Why Use Semantic HTML?</h2>
        <p>Semantic HTML is important because it helps browsers and search engines understand the structure of content. By using tags like <code>&lt;header&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;footer&gt;</code>, the content becomes easier to parse.</p>
        <time datetime="2025-03-09">March 9, 2025</time>
    </article>
    
    <aside>
        <h3>Tip of the Day</h3>
        <p>Remember to use <mark>semantic tags</mark> to make your content more accessible and SEO-friendly!</p>
    </aside>
</section>

<figure>
    <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/300" alt="Web Development" />
    <figcaption>Image showing web development tools</figcaption>
</figure>

<footer>
    <p>Created with ❤️ by Priya</p>
</footer>

</body>
</html>
